{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492377"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:26:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:26:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1041"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1041"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.04,0.06,0.82,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1041"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43231"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1041"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1041"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28216"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"},{"type":"tags","id":"2840"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"6351"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18"},{"type":"contributions","id":"132"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10667"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11093"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16760"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41117"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43231","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43231"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents with a five-day history of increasing pain and swelling in her knee. She had spent an afternoon bushwalking with her husband and noticed the pain 4km into the walk. The pain is worsened by walking and eased by rest. She first noticed this pain 18 months ago and has experienced some stiffness in her legs first thing in the morning, but these symptoms usually rapidly resolve. Since menopause, she has had recurrent urinary tract infections requiring antibiotic treatment. Her past medical history includes hypothyroidism managed with levothyroxine and type 2 diabetes managed on diet by limiting carbohydrate intake and incorporating meat and vegetable consumption to each meal. She has an 8-pack-year smoking history and consumes a glass of wine with dinner each night. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her blood pressure is 135/75 mmHg, pulse 80/min and temperature 37.2C. There is an obvious effusion around her left knee, which is not associated with erythema, tenderness or disproportionate warmth. Her left knee is also noted to have some varus deformity and she has restricted extension/flexion in her knee, due to pain. Crepitus is noted with joint movement, however, there is no joint line tenderness. A plain X-ray confirms the effusion, with some narrowing of the joint space, osteophyte formation along the tibia and femur and mild osteosclerosis identified. An aspirate of clear yellow fluid is obtained, however, microscopy, culture, sensitivity and cytology reports are still pending.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reactive arthritis","Gouty arthropathy","Pseudogout arthropathy","Osteoarthritis","Rheumatoid arthritis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoarthritis (OA)\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis. This is because has an 18-month history of early morning stiffness (EMS) that rapidly resolves with a varus deformity and crepitus is suggestive of chronic joint damage [1]. She has exacerbated her osteoarthritis secondary to strenuous physical activity, which has resulted in pain worse on movement and improved by rest, consistent with osteoarthritis (whereas in rheumatoid arthritis, the reverse is true, indicative of joint inflammation). X-ray findings of loss of joint space, osteophyte and osteosclerosis are also consistent with OA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis (RA) \u003C/strong\u003Eis an autoimmune disorder that has bilateral joint involvements, particularly in the wrists, hands, knees, elbows, shoulders and hips. It can be distinguished from osteoarthritis with EMS that lasts \u0026gt;60 minutes and pain that improves with movement. Furthermore, although both osteoarthritis and rheumatoid arthritis can present with loss of joint space and soft tissue swelling on x-ray, osteophytes are not present in rheumatoid arthritis unless there is concurrent osteoarthritis. X-ray findings consistent with RA would further include the presence of erosions and osteopenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEven though \u003Cstrong\u003Egouty arthropathy \u003C/strong\u003Eand\u003Cstrong\u003E pseudogout arthropathy\u003C/strong\u003E are important differential diagnoses in a patient with acute monoarticular pain at the knee. A common site for pseudogout arthropathy is located at the knee joint. High purine is likely to contribute to gouty arthropathy, however, a high meat diet is not always indicative of high purine levels, as reduced renal excretion (90%) of urate rather than high meat consumption is likely to contribute to gout. Additionally, there is no erythema, warmth or tenderness to make these differentials the most likely diagnosis overall [2]. Furthermore, the aspirate is clear while in gout and pseudogout, the aspirate would be cloudy indicating high cell counts consistent with inflammation. The absence of Xray findings of chondrocalcinosis would also make a diagnosis of pseudogout less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReactive arthritis \u003C/strong\u003Eis a seronegative inflammatory arthropathy. It typically develops after a genitourinary (i.e. chlamydia, gonorrhoea) or gastrointestinal (i.e. campylobacter jejuni, shigella) illness, causing the acute onset of peripheral oligoarthritis which was not evident in this scenario. Her recurrent urinary tract infections (UTI) are likely to be due to low estrogen levels following menopause resulting in vaginal dryness and irritation that predisposes her to UTIs. However, it should be noted that UTI is not a risk factor for reactive arthritis. Furthermore, other symptoms such as fever, malaise, weight loss and fatigue may also be present in reactive arthritis, which were not present and therefore unlikely to be the correct diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Osteoarthritis is a degenerative arthropathy that exacerbates with exercise and improves with rest"],"references":["Doherty, M \u0026 Abhishek, A 2020,\u00a0Clinical manifestations and diagnosis of osteoarthritis, UpToDate, viewed 8 October 2020, \u003Chttps://www-uptodate-com.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/contents/clinical-manifestations-and-diagnosis-of-osteoarthritis?search=osteoarthritis\u0026source=searchresult\u0026selectedTitle=1~150\u0026usagetype=default\u0026display_rank=1\u003E.","Helfgott, S 2020,\u00a0Monoarthritis in adults: Etiology and evaluation, UpToDate, viewed 8 October 2020, \u003Chttps://www-uptodate-com.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/contents/monoarthritis-in-adults-etiology-and-evaluation?search=monoarticular\u0026source=searchresult\u0026selectedTitle=1~43\u0026usagetype=default\u0026display_rank=1\u003E."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28216"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1041"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28216"},"attribu